POPs are generally categorized in three: (1) pesticides that include Aldrin, Chlordane, Dichlorodiphenyltrichloroethane (DDT), Dieldrin, Endrin, Heptachlor, Hexachlorobenzene (HCBs), Mirex, Toxaphene; (2) Industrial chemicals include Polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs) and HCBs; (3) by-products including polychlorinated dibenzo-p-dioxins (PCDD) and polychlorinated dibenzofurans (PCDF), and PCBs (http://chm.pops.int/TheConvention/ThePOPs/The12InitialPOPs/tabid/296/Default.aspx). Furthermore, under Stockholm Convention, certain chemical pollutants such as Alpha hexachlorocyclohexane, Beta hexachlorocyclohexane, Chlordecone, Dicofol, Lindane, Perfluorooctane Sulfonic Acid (PFOS), Perfluorooctane Sulfonyl Fluoride (PFOSF), etc., were recently introduced under the category of new POPs (Fig. 2.3
                  ) (http://chm.pops.int/TheConvention/ThePOPs/TheNewPOPs/tabid/2511/Default.aspx). POPs are considered as one of the major cause of environmental pollution through different day to day operational activities such as agriculture, polluted outcomes from industries and residential societies.
